Chemical interaction among the biopolymers (pectin and gelatin) and the functional fillers (CD and S-CD) was assessed using FTIR analysis (
                        Fig. 3
                        ). The wideband around 3284 cm−1 was due to the O-H stretching and the intermolecular or intramolecular H-bonding, and peaks at 2936 and 2880 cm–1 were due to the C-H stretching vibration of pectin’s methylene and methyl groups [22]. The peak at 1745 cm−1 was due to the CO group of the ester bond of pectin [23]. The peaks that appeared at 1634, 1548, and 1236 cm−1 were assigned to the amide-Ⅰ (CO stretching), amide-Ⅱ (N-H bending), and amide-Ⅲ (C-N and N-H stretching) of gelatin, respectively [24]. The peak observed at 1454 cm−1 was attributed to the pectin carboxyl group's asymmetrical and symmetrical stretching vibration [23]. Peak detected at 1009 cm−1 corresponded to the C-O-C stretching of the saccharide structure of pectin [4]. The FTIR spectra showed the major peaks of pectin and gelatin individually in the pectin/gelatin-based composite film, indicating their compatibility. Although there was some difference between CD and S-CD, their addition slightly changed the FTIR peak position and intensity. Overall, the FTIR results showed good compatibility between the polymer matrix and the nanofillers.
